sentences: Dick Manning (born Samuel Medoff (Самуил Медов), June 12, 1912 – April 11, 1991) was a Russian-born American songwriter, best known for his many collaborations with Al Hoffman.
The Boys From Boise aired on the DuMont Television Network in 1944.
Early years ==
section: == Early years ==

sentences: Manning was born in Gomel, Russian Empire, and came to the United States with his family when he was six years old.
section: == Early years ==

sentences: Manning changed his name from Medoff in 1948.
section: == Early years ==

sentences: In the early 1940s, he had a radio show on WHN radio in New York called Sam Medoff and His Yiddish Swing Orchestra; he performed with his band, "The Yiddish Swingtet".
section: == Yiddish swing ==

sentences: The 15 minute weekly radio show, which blended traditional Yiddish folk music with swing and jazz, got its start on the station in 1938.
section: == Yiddish swing ==

sentences: The radio show was originally done live at the Lowes State Theatre every Sunday at 1PM; it aired until 1955.

sentences: In 1956, Manning shared a late-night subway ride with Perry Como's music publisher, Mickey Glass.
section: == Songwriting and composing ==

sentences: Glass arranged to hear Manning's demo the next day; Como's recording of "Hot Diggity" was the result of that chance meeting of Manning and Glass.
